SIMPLE: seedy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seedy
<hw>Seed"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Seedier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Seediest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Abounding with seeds;
bearing seeds; having run to seeds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having a peculiar flavor supposed to be derived from
the weeds growing among the vines; -- said of certain kinds of French
brandy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Old and worn out; exhausted; spiritless; also, poor
and miserable looking; shabbily clothed; shabby looking; <as>as, he
looked <ex>seedy</ex>; a <ex>seedy</ex> coat</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Little Flanigan here . . . is a little <qex>seedy</qex>, as we say
among us that practice the law.</q> <rj><au>Goldsmith.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Seedy toe</b></col>, <cd>an affection of a horse's foot,
in which a cavity filled with horn powder is formed between the laminae
and the wall of the hoof.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seeing</ent>⟦br⟧
